# Context discipline

Compressed context is the default. Treat memory of prior turns as unreliable; re-read sources each chunk.

## Before editing

1. **Read** the file (or the exact region) you will change. Do not edit from recall.
2. **Grep** for symbols you will call, types you will implement, or patterns you will mirror. Do not invent APIs.
3. **Scope** one coherent slice per turn (one function, one module, one issue subtask). Stop when the slice is done.

## Before stating facts

- File paths, line numbers, schema columns, ADR numbers → must come from a tool read in **this** session.
- If you have not read it this session, say so and read it — do not guess.

## When context is thin

1. Re-open the GitHub issue body (`gh issue view N`) or the user’s stated acceptance criteria.
2. Re-read only the **minimum** canon: `RULES.md` hard stops + the relevant `DESIGN.md` section — not the whole repo.
3. Delegate broad codebase search to an `explore` subagent; keep the parent thread anchored to issue # and criteria.

## Forbidden shortcuts (drive most user-visible errors)

- Implementing from pattern-matched “conventional AI” habits — invoke `conventional-ai-skeptic` when tempted.
- Marking work complete without command output from the relevant `just` target.
- Editing user-authored docs (`DESIGN.md`, `GLOSSARY.md`, `RULES.md`, `STANDARDS.md`, `OPERATIONS.md`, `README.md`) without explicit user instruction.
